# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aluminium-sulfate-data-page
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate-data-page] This page provides supplementary chemical data on aluminium sulfate.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate-data-page] The handling of this chemical may incur notable safety precautions.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate-data-page] It is highly recommend that you seek the Material Safety Datasheet (MSDS) for this chemical from a reliable source and follow its directions.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] The anhydrous form occurs naturally as a rare mineral millosevichite, found for example in volcanic environments and on burning coal-mining waste dumps.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Aluminium sulfate is rarely, if ever, encountered as the anhydrous salt.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] It forms a number of different hydrates, of which the hexadecahydrate Al2(SO4)3·16H2O and octadecahydrate Al2(SO4)3·18H2O are the most common.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] The heptadecahydrate, whose formula can be written as [Al(H2O)6]2(SO4)3·5H2O, occurs naturally as the mineral alunogen.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Aluminium sulfate is sometimes called **alum** or **papermaker's alum** in certain industries.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] However, the name "alum" is more commonly and properly used for any double sulfate salt with the generic formula *X*Al(SO4)2·12H2O, where *X* is a monovalent cation such as potassium or ammonium.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] The alum schists employed in the manufacture of aluminium sulfate are mixtures of iron pyrite, aluminium silicate and various bituminous substances, and are found in upper Bavaria, Bohemia, Belgium, and Scotland.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] These are either roasted or exposed to the weathering action of the air.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] In the roasting process, sulfuric acid is formed and acts on the clay to form aluminium sulfate, a similar condition of affairs being produced during weathering.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] The mass is now systematically extracted with water, and a solution of aluminium sulfate of specific gravity 1.16 is prepared.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] This solution is allowed to stand for some time (in order that any calcium sulfate and basic iron(III) sulfate may separate), and is then evaporated until iron(II) sulfate crystallizes on cooling; it is then drawn off and evaporated until it attains a specific gravity of 1.40.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] It is now allowed to stand for some time, and decanted from any sediment.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] In the preparation of aluminium sulfate from clays or from bauxite, the material is gently calcined, then mixed with sulfuric acid and water and heated gradually to boiling; if concentrated acid is used no external heat is generally required as the formation of aluminium sulfate is exothermic.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] It is allowed to stand for some time, and the clear solution is drawn off.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] When cryolite is used as the ore, it is mixed with calcium carbonate and heated.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] By this means, sodium aluminate is formed; it is then extracted with water and precipitated either by sodium bicarbonate or by passing a current of carbon dioxide through the solution.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] The precipitate is then dissolved in sulfuric acid.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Aluminium sulfate is sometimes used in the human food industry as a firming agent, where it takes on E number **E520**, and in animal feed as a bactericide.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] In the United States, the FDA lists it as "generally recognized as safe" with no limit on concentration.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Aluminium sulfate may be used as a deodorant, an astringent, or as a styptic for superficial shaving wounds.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Aluminium sulfate is used as a mordant in dyeing and printing textiles.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Aluminium sulfate is used in water purification and for chemical phosphorus removal from wastewater.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] It causes suspended impurities to coagulate into larger particles and then settle to the bottom of the container (or be filtered out) more easily.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] This process is called coagulation or flocculation.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Research suggests that in Australia, aluminium sulfate used in this way in drinking water treatment is the primary source of hydrogen sulfide gas in sanitary sewer systems.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] An improper and excess application incident in 1988 polluted the water supply of Camelford in Cornwall.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Aluminium sulfate has been used as a method of eutrophication remediation for shallow lakes.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] It works by reducing the phosphorus load in the lakes.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] When dissolved in a large amount of neutral or slightly alkaline water, aluminium sulfate produces a gelatinous precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] In dyeing and printing cloth, the gelatinous precipitate helps the dye adhere to the clothing fibers by rendering the pigment insoluble.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Aluminium sulfate is sometimes used to reduce the pH of garden soil, as it hydrolyzes to form the aluminium hydroxide precipitate and a dilute sulfuric acid solution.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] An example of what changing the pH level of soil can do to plants is visible when looking at *Hydrangea macrophylla*.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] The gardener can add aluminium sulfate to the soil to reduce the pH which in turn will result in the flowers of the *Hydrangea* turning a different color (blue).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] The aluminium is what makes the flowers blue; at a higher pH, the aluminium is not available to the plant.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] In the construction industry, it is used as waterproofing agent and accelerator in concrete.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Another use is a foaming agent in fire fighting foam.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] It can also be very effective as a molluscicide, killing spanish slugs.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] The compound decomposes to γ-alumina and sulfur trioxide when heated between 580 and 900 °C.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] It combines with water forming hydrated salts of various compositions.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] The carbon dioxide is trapped by the foam stabilizer and creates a thick foam which will float on top of hydrocarbon fuels and seal off access to atmospheric oxygen, smothering the fire.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Chemical foam was unsuitable for use on polar solvents such as alcohol, as the fuel would mix with and break down the foam blanket.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] The carbon dioxide generated also served to propel the foam out of the container, be it a portable fire extinguisher or fixed installation using hoselines.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/aluminium-sulfate] Chemical foam is considered obsolete in the United States and has been replaced by synthetic mechanical foams, such as AFFF which have a longer shelf life, are more effective, and more versatile, although some countries such as Japan and India continue to use it.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] A **safety data sheet** (**SDS**), **material safety data sheet** (**MSDS**), or **product safety data sheet** (**PSDS**) is a document that lists information relating to occupational safety and health for the use of various substances and products.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] SDSs are a widely used type of fact sheet used to catalogue information on chemical species including chemical compounds and chemical mixtures.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] SDS information may include instructions for the safe use and potential hazards associated with a particular material or product, along with spill-handling procedures.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The older MSDS formats could vary from source to source within a country depending on national requirements; however, the newer SDS format is internationally standardized.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] An SDS for a substance is not primarily intended for use by the general consumer, focusing instead on the hazards of working with the material in an occupational setting.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] There is also a duty to properly label substances on the basis of physico-chemical, health, or environmental risk.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Labels often include hazard symbols such as the European Union standard symbols.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The same product (e.g. paints sold under identical brand names by the same company) can have different formulations in different countries.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The formulation and hazards of a product using a generic name may vary between manufacturers in the same country.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The Globally Harmonized System of Classification and Labelling of Chemicals contains a standard specification for safety data sheets.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The SDS follows a 16 section format which is internationally agreed and for substances especially, the SDS should be followed with an Annex which contains the exposure scenarios of this particular substance.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] In Canada, the program known as the Workplace Hazardous Materials Information System (WHMIS) establishes the requirements for SDSs in workplaces and is administered federally by Health Canada under the Hazardous Products Act, Part II, and the Controlled Products Regulations.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Safety data sheets have been made an integral part of the system of Regulation (EC) No 1907/2006 (REACH).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The SDS must be supplied in an official language of the Member State(s) where the substance or mixture is placed on the market, unless the Member State(s) concerned provide(s) otherwise (Article 31(5) of REACH).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The European Chemicals Agency (ECHA) has published a guidance document on the compilation of safety data sheets.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] In Germany, safety data sheets must be compiled in accordance with REACH Regulation No.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The requirements concerning national aspects are defined in the Technical Rule for Hazardous Substances (TRGS) 220 "National aspects when compiling safety data sheets".
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] A national measure mentioned in SDS section 15 is as example the water hazard class (WGK) it is based on regulations governing systems for handling substances hazardous to waters (AwSV).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Dutch Safety Data Sheets are well known as veiligheidsinformatieblad or Chemiekaarten.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] This is a collection of Safety Data Sheets of the most widely used chemicals.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The Chemiekaarten boek is commercially available, but also made available through educational institutes, such as the web site offered by the University of Groningen.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] This section contributes to a better understanding of the regulations governing SDS within the South African framework.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] As regulations may change, it is the responsibility of the reader to verify the validity of the regulations mentioned in text.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] As globalisation increased and countries engaged in cross-border trade, the quantity of hazardous material crossing international borders amplified.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Realising the detrimental effects of hazardous trade, the United Nations established a committee of experts specialising in the transportation of hazardous goods.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The committee provides best practises governing the conveyance of hazardous materials and goods for land including road and railway; air as well as sea transportation.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] These best practises are constantly updated to remain current and relevant.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] These guidelines prescribed by the international authorities are applicable to the South African land, sea and air transportation of hazardous materials and goods.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] In addition to these rules and regulations to International best practice, South Africa has also implemented common laws which are laws based on custom and practise.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Common laws are a vital part of maintaining public order and forms the basis of case laws.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Case laws, using the principles of common law are interpretations and decisions of statutes made by courts.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Acts of parliament are determinations and regulations by parliament which form the foundation of statutory law.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Statutory laws are published in the government gazette or on the official website.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Lastly, subordinate legislation are the bylaws issued by local authorities and authorised by parliament.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Statutory law gives effect to the Occupational Health and Safety Act of 1993 and the National Road Traffic Act of 1996.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The Occupational Health and Safety Act details the necessary provisions for the safe handling and storage of hazardous materials and goods whilst the transport act details with the necessary provisions for the transportation of the hazardous goods.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Relevant South African legislation includes the Hazardous Chemicals Agent regulations of 2021 under the Occupational Health and Safety Act of 1993, the Chemical Substance Act 15 of 1973, and the National Road Traffic Act of 1996, and the Standards Act of 2008.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] There has been selective incorporation of aspects of the Globally Harmonised System (GHS) of Classification and Labelling of Chemicals into South African legislation.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] At each point of the chemical value chain, there is a responsibility to manage chemicals in a safe and responsible manner.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] A SDS is included in the requirements of Occupational Health and Safety Act, 1993 (Act No.85 of 1993) Regulation 1179 dated 25 August 1995.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The categories of information supplied in the SDS are listed in SANS 11014:2010; dangerous goods standards – Classification and information.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] In the U.K., the Chemicals (Hazard Information and Packaging for Supply) Regulations 2002 - known as CHIP Regulations - impose duties upon suppliers, and importers into the EU, of hazardous materials.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] NOTE: Safety data sheets (SDS) are no longer covered by the CHIP regulations.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The laws that require a SDS to be provided have been transferred to the European REACH Regulations.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The Control of Substances Hazardous to Health (COSHH) Regulations govern the use of hazardous substances in the workplace in the UK and specifically require an assessment of the use of a substance.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Regulation 12 requires that an employer provides employees with information, instruction and training for people exposed to hazardous substances.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] This duty would be very nearly impossible without the data sheet as a starting point.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] It is important for employers therefore to insist on receiving a data sheet from a supplier of a substance.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The duty to supply information is not confined to informing only business users of products.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] SDSs for retail products sold by large DIY shops are usually obtainable on those companies' web sites.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Web sites of manufacturers and large suppliers do not always include them even if the information is obtainable from retailers but written or telephone requests for paper copies will usually be responded to favourably.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The United Nations (UN) defines certain details used in SDSs such as the UN numbers used to identify some hazardous materials in a standard form while in international transit.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] In the U.S., the Occupational Safety and Health Administration requires that SDSs be readily available to all employees for potentially harmful substances handled in the workplace under the Hazard Communication Standard.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The SDS is also required to be made available to local fire departments and local and state emergency planning officials under Section 311 of the Emergency Planning and Community Right-to-Know Act.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The American Chemical Society defines Chemical Abstracts Service Registry Numbers (CAS numbers) which provide a unique number for each chemical and are also used internationally in SDSs.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Reviews of material safety data sheets by the U.S.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation Board have detected dangerous deficiencies.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] The board's Combustible Dust Hazard Study analyzed 140 data sheets of substances capable of producing combustible dusts.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] None of the SDSs contained all the information the board said was needed to work with the material safely, and 41 percent failed to even mention that the substance was combustible.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] As part of its study of an explosion and fire that destroyed the Barton Solvents facility in Valley Center, Kansas, in 2007, the safety board reviewed 62 material safety data sheets for commonly used nonconductive flammable liquids.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] As in the combustible dust study, the board found all the data sheets inadequate.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] In 2012, the US adopted the 16 section Safety Data Sheet to replace Material Safety Data Sheets.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] This became effective on 1 December 2013.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] These new Safety Data Sheets comply with the Globally Harmonized System of Classification and Labeling of Chemicals (GHS).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] By 1 June 2015, employers were required to have their workplace labeling and hazard communication programs updated as necessary – including all MSDSs replaced with SDS-formatted documents.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Many companies offer the service of collecting, or writing and revising, data sheets to ensure they are up to date and available for their subscribers or users.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] Some jurisdictions impose an explicit duty of care that each SDS be regularly updated, usually every three to five years.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] However, when new information becomes available, the SDS must be revised without delay.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/material-safety-data-sheet] If a full SDS is not feasible, then a reduced workplace label should be authored.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Many technical publications (books, journals, advertisements for equipment and machinery) simply state "standard conditions" without specifying them, often substituting the term with older "normal conditions", or "NC".
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] In special cases this can lead to confusion and errors.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Good practice always incorporates the reference conditions of temperature and pressure.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] If not stated, some room environment conditions are supposed, close to 1 atm pressure, 25 °C (77.00 °F), and 0% humidity.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] IUPAC also defines SATP (Standard Ambient Temperature and Pressure) as a temperature of 298.15 K (25.00 °C; 77.00 °F) and an absolute pressure of exactly 1 atm (101.325 kPa).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] This standard is also called **normal temperature and pressure** (abbreviated as **NTP**).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] However, a common temperature and pressure in use by NIST for thermodynamic experiments is 298.15 K (25.00 °C; 77.00 °F) and 1 bar (100.000 kPa).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] NIST also uses 15 °C (288.15 K; 59.00 °F) for the temperature compensation of refined petroleum products, despite noting that these two values are not exactly consistent with each other.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] The **ISO 13443** standard reference conditions for natural gas and similar fluids are 288.15 K (15.00 °C; 59.00 °F) and 1 atm (101.325 kPa); by contrast, the American Petroleum Institute adopts 60 °F (15.56 °C; 288.71 K).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Before 1918, many professionals and scientists using the metric system of units defined the standard reference conditions of temperature and pressure for expressing gas volumes as being 15 °C (288.15 K; 59.00 °F) and 101.325 kPa (1.00 atm; 760 Torr).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] During those same years, the most commonly used standard reference conditions for people using the imperial or U.S. customary systems was 60 °F (15.56 °C; 288.71 K) and 14.696 psi (1.00 atm) because it was almost universally used by the oil and gas industries worldwide.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] The above definitions are no longer the most commonly used in either system of units.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Many different definitions of standard reference conditions are currently being used by organizations all over the world.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] The table below lists a few of them, but there are more.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Some of these organizations used other standards in the past.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] For example, IUPAC's new value is the mean atmospheric pressure at an altitude of about 112 metres, which is closer to the worldwide median altitude of human habitation (194 m), and follows the metric system (Pascal is a metric unit, while atmosphere is not).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Natural gas companies in Europe, Australia, and South America have adopted 15 °C (288.15 K; 59.00 °F) and 1 atm (101.325 kPa) as their standard gas volume reference conditions, used as the base values for defining the standard cubic meter.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Also, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) each have more than one definition of standard reference conditions in their various standards and regulations.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] In aeronautics and fluid dynamics the "International Standard Atmosphere" (ISA) is a specification of pressure, temperature, density, and speed of sound at each altitude.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] At standard mean sea level it specifies a temperature of 15 °C (59 °F), pressure of 101,325 pascals (14.6959 psi) (1 atm), and a density of 1.2250 kilograms per cubic meter (0.07647 lb/cu ft).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] It also specifies a temperature lapse rate of −6.5 °C (−11.7 °F) per km (approximately −2 °C (−3.6 °F) per 1,000 ft).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] The International Standard Atmosphere is representative of atmospheric conditions at mid latitudes.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] In the US this information is specified the U.S.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Standard Atmosphere which is identical to the "International Standard Atmosphere" at all altitudes up to 65,000 feet above sea level.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Because many definitions of standard temperature and pressure differ in temperature significantly from standard laboratory temperatures (e.g.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] 0 °C vs. ~28 °C), reference is often made to "standard laboratory conditions" (a term deliberately chosen to be different from the term "standard conditions for temperature and pressure", despite its semantic near identity when interpreted literally).
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] However, what is a "standard" laboratory temperature and pressure is inevitably geography-bound, given that different parts of the world differ in climate, altitude and the degree of use of heat/cooling in the workplace.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] For example, schools in New South Wales, Australia use 25 °C at 100 kPa for standard laboratory conditions.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] ASTM International has published Standard ASTM E41- Terminology Relating to Conditioning and hundreds of special conditions for particular materials and test methods.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Other standards organizations also have specialized standard test conditions.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] It is as important to indicate the applicable reference conditions of temperature and pressure when stating the molar volume of a gas as it is when expressing a gas volume or volumetric flow rate.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Stating the molar volume of a gas without indicating the reference conditions of temperature and pressure has very little meaning and can cause confusion.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] The molar volume of gases around STP and at atmospheric pressure can be calculated with an accuracy that is usually sufficient by using the ideal gas law.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] Technical literature can be confusing because many authors fail to explain whether they are using the ideal gas constant *R*, or the specific gas constant *R*s.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] The relationship between the two constants is *R*s = *R* / *m*, where *m* is the molecular mass of the gas.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] The US Standard Atmosphere (USSA) uses 8.31432 m3·Pa/(mol·K) as the value of *R*.
[src:aluminium-sulfate-data-page/standard-temperature-and-pressure] However, the USSA in 1976 does recognize that this value is not consistent with the values of the Avogadro constant and the Boltzmann constant.
